The paper deals with the algebraic factorization of multivariate polynomials, which is a topic in algebraic geometry (cs.AG) and computational algebra (cs.SC). The use of resultants and discriminants is a common technique in computational algebra, and the paper specifically focuses on iterative univariate resultant constructions, which falls under the subcategory of computational algebra (cs.SC). The paper also mentions a geometric interpretation of the algebraic factorization of the iterated discriminant of a single polynomial, which suggests a connection to algebraic geometry (cs.AG) and topology (cs.GT). The paper also uses induction on the degree of the polynomials, which is a common technique in symbolic computation (cs.SY) and computational algebra (cs.SC). Finally, the paper deals with explicit decompositions into irreducible factors, which is a topic in computational algebra (cs.SC) and computer algebraic geometry (cs.CA).
